"/> Maybe posting upside down confused you, but you're missing something
in your analysis.

The OP paid _two_ things, $9 cash and a coupon that gave the right
to $1 off. To undo the sale, the OP must get back both of the things
he gave up.

As a matter of law, he's not entitled to the extra $1 in cash, but
to the $1 coupon. If the store can't return it to him -- which it
probably can't -- then the next best thing is to give him the $1.

People have raised the red herring of &quot;schemes to convert coupons to
cash.&quot; It staggers the imagination to think anybody would go to this
much trouble to convert _one_ coupon for _one_ dollar to cash. As
far as we've been told, if I remember rightly, the return was made
based on malfunction or misrepresentation of the item.

