&gt;Why would someone return a product and then go back to the store and
&gt;buy the very same item later?

"/> Off the top of my head, several reasons why someone might return a
product and go back to the store and buy the same item later:

a) It was bought for a particular event, ended up not being used at
that event, but the buyer might need it later at a similar event, and
does not wish to store it / does not have space to store it / does not
wish for the money to remain invested in it / it is perishable and
does not want it to spoil before then.

b) The particular unit being returned is defective, and the buyer turns
out to no longer need a non-defective unit immediately (e.g., because
the need for it passed after the buyer discovered it was defective) but
may need it at some point in the future.

c) The buyer will not need to buy the same item again, but someone he
knows might; just as the coupon he used was transferable, the voucher
given to him by the store would and should be transferable as well.

